The Ballad of the Bride, A Papa Don’t Preach Production, now playing at Kala Ghoda, Mumbai 📍

In moving together, 
they unfurl a journey;
In each other's arms, 
a romantic re-discovery.

They see the hope, 
they see the light;
They feel the bliss, 
their eager hearts unite.

They lay their eyes on each other with pride;
There they stand, 
glorious and sing,
The Ballad of the Bride.

@theweddingfilmer has seen love in all its forms—on-screen, off-screen, in grand Bollywood romances, and in the rawness of his own life. From marriage to divorce, losing love to finding it again, he reflects on it all, sharing the lessons, emotions, and realities.

Bollywood makes love look effortless, but reality is far from a perfect script. In this candid conversation, he opens up about the emotions that shaped him, the impact of the people around us, and why love—no matter how messy—can be a beautiful emotion to feel.

A cold email to Shah Rukh Khan turned into a dream job, and a front-row seat to the magic of storytelling. But just when everything seemed set, fate had other plans—leading @theweddingfilmer back to Ghana, where he had to start from scratch.

When he finally returned to India, the industry barely recognized wedding filmmaking as an art. But he didn’t just step in—he transformed it. Today, @theweddingfilmer isn’t just a filmmaker; he’s the name that redefined what it takes to capture love.

On this episode of Hashtag Preach, @theweddingfilmer takes us on an extraordinary journey—from working with Shah Rukh Khan to starting over in Ghana and transforming the wedding film industry. He shares deeply personal stories of heartbreak, reinvention, and the moments that shaped his art. In this conversation he shares some game-changing insights on bespoke wedding music, making your space in this industry, and the future of AI in filmmaking. This isn’t just a conversation—it’s a masterclass in resilience, creativity, and innovation.
